<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>HOUSE OF COMONS TRANSPORT COMMITTEE</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Written evidence from the Automobile Association (WRT 054)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The AA is the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s largest motoring organisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> President, Edmund King, Visiting Professor of Transport of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Newcastle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> University chairs the Department for Transport’s Motorists’ Forum.  The AA is very active stakeholder engaged in wide ranging policy and operational issues relating to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> roads.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The AA keenly engages with its members.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AA members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> views and compl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aints </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are obtained directly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">via telephone calls, letters and e-mails.  The AA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Populus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> panel is the largest motoring opinion panel in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Europe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and more than 20,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">000 respond to our monthly polls</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  Questions on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> roads feature regularly in the polls.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AA members</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have differing views on many key motoring issues</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Most say that roads are in a fairly poor state and have not kept pace with traffic growth. Congestion and unreliable journeys are a significant concern for motorists and business. A majority of AA/</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Populus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> panel members support the construction of new and improved roads.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Motorists accept they mus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">t pay for their motoring but </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">resent b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eing seen </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as a ‘problem’ and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oppose</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> escalating costs such as fuel, road tax, parking charges and pot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ential congestion charges. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rivate motoring is an essential part of 21</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> century life and is something people continue to aspire to and even enjoy. Motoring is the main form of transport for 86% of passenger journeys.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Many people are dependent on the car and the mobility of the car</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> benefits society in many ways.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2. Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AA members support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the construction and improvement of roads.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£46bn is collected from motoring taxes but the proportion of this invested in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">national</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> road network is insufficient.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Motorists are resistant to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">paying more through tolls – especially when they see massive investment bias towards rail.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are many congestion hot-spots on the strategic road network which take too long to eradicate and action is often piecemeal.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Plans to utilise the hard shoulder </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of motorways under ‘managed motorway’ (now called ‘smart motorway’) regimes is risky and short-sighted.  AA members have significant safety concerns.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Too little investment in road maintenance risks creating an unsustainable backlog, traffic delays and acci</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dents.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AA members do not support </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">England</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> strategic roads being operated and managed as a roads ‘utility’.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road users, whilst a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">lso improving the environment?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The scale of the task required </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to transform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the quality, reliability and value to customers of strategic roads is enormous.  In our surveys people show concern for the lack of attention paid to roads our most valuable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">transport asset:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">72% disagree with the statement that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘the government and local councils recognise that people want to own and use cars and are doing what they can to facilitate that’</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AA – </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Populus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">panel members </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">said </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">new roads should be built or major road</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> improvements carried out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">:</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> towns and cities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  67% agree (27% strongly), 11% disagree</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, 22% neither</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> main roads in rural areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, 66% agree (27% strongly),</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">14% disagree</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, 20% neither</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by-pass communities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  78% agree (37% strongly) 8% disagree</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, 15% neither </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> make roads safer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  82% agree (42% strongly) 6% disagree</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, 13% neither</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">71% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of panel members </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agree</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (36% strongly) that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">new motorways and 'strategic roads' – which link cities, areas of population, ports and airports - should be built</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, 14</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">% disagreed with this statement, 15% neither agreed or disagreed;</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The new approach to strategic roads should provide scope for greater levels of investment which in turn could lead to schemes which enhance the environment through better quality quiet surf</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">aces, better drainage and also allow more tunnels and community by-passes.  The popularity of and need for by-passes is often overlooked in road development today.  There is more emphasis on ‘making best use’ which is often really means there is no finance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to do more than a minimum to keep roads maintained and functioning.    </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Despite expectations over many years that government policy and guidance would lead to a truly integrated transport system in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Britain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> it would be hard to describe the system as such. Much has been done to improve network quality and customer experience on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">road and rail and in cities but in many places transport remains a fragmented service.  This is perhaps unsurprising with most journeys being undertaken by road.  Cities and urban areas provide multi-faceted forms of transport with almost around the clock </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">access whereas in rural areas cars and roads remain a lifeline and the mainstay for most.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">One problem in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Britain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is the lack of proper interchanges between the modes at the most opportune places.  The problem is compounded on roads where different authorit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ies are responsible for national and local roads.  Problems on the Highways Agency network may </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">well emanate from a local road which blocks access or egress to or from the national roads network.  Local authorities may also place a different priority on act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ions to resolve such issues.      </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How reliable is the Government’s forecast for growth in demand for the strategic road network? How should the Government deal with uncertainty in its forecast</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Traffic growth forecasts have in general </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">helped predict like</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly future demand with sufficient accuracy to allow policy development.  Uncertainties will always exist but longer term trends have generally been reflected in the models. The problem is not so much the accuracy of the forecasts but the transformation of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hem into policies that lead to realistic capacity improvement.  Too many of our strategic roads run at or over design capacity – which suggests that for decades our predications may have been largely correct but our ability to provide for them in response </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">has been inadequate. The models may place slightly too much faith in the success of interventions like demand management or public transport improvement.  It is also hard to build in the impact of real behaviour and response to political intervention and p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">olicy shifts.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network? What impact will new technology have?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In reality </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">we cannot ignore the capacity constraints which exist on the strategic road network or believe we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can deal with them through unrealistic interventions or expectations.  It is likely that traffic growth will continue for many decades and yet there is belief that ‘making best use’ and behavioural change will prevent ‘overheating’ of traffic demand.  Reli</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ability and efficiency can be improved by relatively soft measures like traffic information, better traffic and incident management and behavioural change.  However, this must go hand in hand with long term planning for upgrading capacity.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The AA believes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">that managed motorways which utilise active traffic management techniques can play a major role in squeezing greater efficiency from key sections of English motorways.  However, we believe these techniques do not provide a long term solution to serious cap</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">acity weaknesses.  The AA is very disappointed that the latest managed motorways will require the permanent conversion of the hard shoulder into a running lane.  AA members are very dubious about this and the Sunday Times featured the results of an AA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Popu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> poll (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) in an article on the 5 May 2013:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">87% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of respondents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">say hard shoulders are what help make motorways safe</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">63% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of respondents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">say they will be more nervous driving on m/way with no h/shoulder</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">77% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of respondents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">don’t agree that hard shoulders ar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e no longer needed because cars are more reliable</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">92% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of respondents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">think having no hard shoulder will make it more difficult to deal with incidents</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Conversely 57% </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of respondents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">agree many sections of motorway are chronically congested and using the hard</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> shoulder makes sense</span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Whilst hard economic times forced a review of capacity improvement costs which led to changes in managed motorway design there will be a need in the not too distant future for further capacity improvements on the sections of managed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">motorway implemented without hard shoulder.  The Highways Agency future congestion maps appear to confirm that some of these managed motorways will indeed be under stress again by 2025?           </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What mechanisms are there for Government to increase inves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">tment in strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The AA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> considers that road users are the investors in the strategic roads network and provide an adequate revenue stream thro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ugh the tax they pay.  Whilst in the future fuel duties may decline because of improved fuel economy there will still be a significant surplus from fuel duty receipts.  Of course it is accepted that a significant proportion of motoring tax revenues are use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d for the general exchequer and so we understand the need for supporting investment in England’s strategic roads from other means.    This does not extend to accepting the need for further fiscal input from road users through direct charges on some roads. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The AA opposes the proposal to charge drivers to use the A14 once it is upgraded, an AA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Populus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> poll in 2012 (iii) found:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">63% of respondents </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">disagreed (38% strongly) that p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">eople using roads that need widening should be charged by the mile to use those roa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ds to pay for the road’s improvement.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">AA members also rejected the idea of creating a roads utility – an AA </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Populus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> poll (ii) found:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">64% of respondents disagreed (54% strongly) that strategic roads should be funded, operated and organised by private </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">companies.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 23.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How should the Highways Agency be reformed to make it “the world’s leading highway operator”? What roles should Government and the private sector play to ensure better management of the strategic road network?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Highways Agency has a relative</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly small strategic road network compared to others around the world. In fact it does not even operate roads in Scotland or Wales and yet those networks have a direct relationship with HA roads.  Whilst it is good to have ambitions for the HA to be the ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> leading road operator’ it will take time under its new remit to achieve this.  The HA can learn much from road authorities around the world but the HA strategic roads are quite unique.  The UK is densely populated with very heavy road traffic flows and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> HA roads critically link with numerous local authority roads over which it has no control.  The HA strategic network has developed relatively piecemeal with past political intervention leading to stop-go policies and many unresolved capacity problems.  In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recent times the public has also been less enthusiastic to support major capacity improvements.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The redefined HA should seek to engage even better than at present and work to renew public interest in road development and improvement. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">)  21,510 respons</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es to AA-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Populus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Poll 15-19 April 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(ii) 20,161 responses to AA-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Populus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Poll 22-28 March 2012 </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">(iii) 15,860 responses to AA-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Populus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Poll 20-27 July 2011</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>